snippet.textDisplay:
I've been a long supporter of Avi, but there are a couple of key points missed.

1. Djokovic's first appeal wasn't won on the merit of his argument, it was won on procedural grounds. In other words, the court overturned the visa cancellation not because it agreed with the validity of his medical exemption, but because Border Force officials didn't follow correct procedure in the process of cancelling his visa.

2. You can drill on what reason the minister used to cancel his visa the second time, but the reality is he likely just gathered a lot of legal advice and just chose to go with the reason that he has the highest chance to win with in court, i.e. hardest to disprove because the burden of proof isn't on the minister in terms of this discretionary power, according to legislation. He probably didn't care what reason he used as long as it could win him the case, so stop drilling so much on the reason, he could've used many other reasons but chose the easiest one to win with, simple as that.
